00:47:18,425 --> 00:47:20,508
and that we would see him in cinematics and cut scenes.

1011
00:47:20,828 --> 00:47:23,392
So we were playing a character just like a third person

1012
00:47:23,913 --> 00:47:24,734
action adventure game.

1013
00:47:25,094 --> 00:47:26,136
But there are games like Half-Life.

1014
00:47:27,188 --> 00:47:31,493
Half-Life 2, one of my favorite games, where the character is a cypher, right?

1015
00:47:31,513 --> 00:47:36,098
They don't have a personality because you want to transport your personality into them.

1016
00:47:36,679 --> 00:47:37,680
Now that's really cool.

1017
00:47:37,780 --> 00:47:42,586
I think there's something really important about that, but if you want to have your character

1018
00:47:42,626 --> 00:47:43,007
go on an arc...

1019
00:47:44,367 --> 00:47:48,970
it's all then about the reflection of that art has to come from your support cast and from the world itself.

1020
00:47:49,471 --> 00:47:54,314
So the lift is now on the environment artists, the lift is on the supporting cast

1021
00:47:54,675 --> 00:47:57,197
to help reflect back what my actions did.

1022
00:47:57,917 --> 00:48:00,519
So this is a constant battle we have as game developers is

1023
00:48:01,260 --> 00:48:04,823
when we want to tell a story which has a prescribed beginning and end,

1024
00:48:06,264 --> 00:48:10,145
And that conflicts with a goal that a player might have.

1025
00:48:10,685 --> 00:48:12,386
You have what we call cognitive dissonance,

1026
00:48:12,426 --> 00:48:13,806
and it's something that we dealt with a lot.

1027
00:48:13,826 --> 00:48:15,267
Like, hey, I wouldn't have felt that way

1028
00:48:15,687 --> 00:48:16,787
if I shot that person.

1029
00:48:16,807 --> 00:48:19,188
I would have felt happy about it, not sad about it.

1030
00:48:19,888 --> 00:48:22,929
So one of our challenges as game developers

1031
00:48:23,109 --> 00:48:25,790
is how do we ensure that we have parity

1032
00:48:26,830 --> 00:48:28,210
with what the character's feeling

1033
00:48:28,250 --> 00:48:30,211
and what the audience member might be feeling?

1034
00:48:31,186 --> 00:48:34,247
And that's why first-person shooters that let you be a cypher,

1035
00:48:34,287 --> 00:48:37,268
or let that first-person character not have a personality,

1036
00:48:37,688 --> 00:48:40,349
that's probably the cleanest and easiest way to do that.

1037
00:48:40,809 --> 00:48:44,110
But I challenge all of us to think about telling stories completely,

1038
00:48:44,310 --> 00:48:47,651
all the way through, and retaining that connection with the character

1039
00:48:47,991 --> 00:48:49,031
and the way the player feels.

1040
00:48:49,991 --> 00:48:53,792
And I know it's something that I've got friends over here from Naughty Dog,

1041
00:48:53,832 --> 00:48:55,513
it's something I'm sure you guys talk about a lot.

1042
00:48:56,233 --> 00:48:57,814
And I worked with Taylor and Jacob,

1043
00:48:58,355 --> 00:48:59,876
and they worked on The Last of Us,

1044
00:48:59,896 --> 00:49:01,617
and it's one of my favorite games of all time.

1045
00:49:02,098 --> 00:49:03,038
And I remember telling him,

1046
00:49:03,058 --> 00:49:05,240
hey, my only beef with that game was at the end,

1047
00:49:05,260 --> 00:49:08,543
I wouldn't have made the same decisions Joel made.

1048
00:49:09,183 --> 00:49:10,845
But what they told me was really compelling.

1049
00:49:10,945 --> 00:49:12,606
They said, well, that wasn't your story.

1050
00:49:12,987 --> 00:49:14,047
That was Joel's story.

1051
00:49:14,668 --> 00:49:16,710
And as long as you're with him along the line,

1052
00:49:17,170 --> 00:49:19,412
you'll understand and appreciate that decision

1053
00:49:19,552 --> 00:49:20,813
that he made for himself.

1054
00:49:21,413 --> 00:49:22,895
So those are the kind of challenges we have

1055
00:49:23,115 --> 00:49:24,956
as designers and as artists,

1056
00:49:25,437 --> 00:49:28,860
is to try our best to tell compelling emotional stories,

1057
00:49:29,520 --> 00:49:32,683
yet embrace the agency that is in video games.

1058
00:49:33,744 --> 00:49:34,044
Thank you.

1059
00:49:34,624 --> 00:49:34,884
Thank you.

1060
00:49:35,765 --> 00:49:36,586
Hi. Hi.

1061
00:49:36,846 --> 00:49:40,089
Could you talk more about designing female protagonists?

1062
00:49:40,309 --> 00:49:41,590
Like, what are the challenges

1063
00:49:41,670 --> 00:49:43,351
and what are the things you have to keep in mind?

1064
00:49:44,260 --> 00:49:47,842
Yeah, when it comes to female protagonists, I don't think that's important.

1065
00:49:49,483 --> 00:49:51,303
I'm going to say that one more time, it's not important.

1066
00:49:52,084 --> 00:49:53,124
The hero is the hero.

1067
00:49:54,084 --> 00:49:57,806
Now, am I saying is there a difference between a man and a woman?

1068
00:49:57,906 --> 00:49:58,486
Absolutely.

1069
00:49:58,947 --> 00:50:02,228
But you just build that into part of who they are as a character.

1070
00:50:04,743 --> 00:50:07,724
The only reason I can say that there's a problem with it right now is because people still

1071
00:50:07,824 --> 00:50:09,965
obsess about it as a thing, right?

1072
00:50:10,185 --> 00:50:15,066
Being a female, oh my gosh, I'm a dude and I feel really uncomfortable playing as a female

1073
00:50:15,086 --> 00:50:16,366
and I don't know how that makes me feel.

1074
00:50:16,926 --> 00:50:19,307
That can exist and some people have issues with that.

1075
00:50:19,687 --> 00:50:23,388
But really what we're trying to get to is a place is that your character is your character.

1076
00:50:23,948 --> 00:50:28,589
They can be female and they can be an alien, they can be a man, they can be a piece of

1077
00:50:28,669 --> 00:50:30,389
slime, they can be whatever you want.

1078
00:50:30,989 --> 00:50:34,330
But ultimately, does their motivations ring true?

1079
00:50:35,491 --> 00:50:38,411
Does the characters actions reflect their motivations?

1080
00:50:40,372 --> 00:50:41,192
Are they compelling?

1081
00:50:41,472 --> 00:50:42,293
Are they interesting?

1082
00:50:42,553 --> 00:50:44,093
Do they have some place to go?

1083
00:50:44,113 --> 00:50:46,374
And as long as you have all of those things

1084
00:50:46,434 --> 00:50:49,255
and you could take, the reason that this presentation

1085
00:50:49,295 --> 00:50:52,676
was so much more about the structure of your hero

1086
00:50:52,736 --> 00:50:55,117
and not so much about the choices you make

1087
00:50:55,697 --> 00:50:57,177
is because once you have that right,

1088
00:50:58,018 --> 00:50:59,878
you can really design pretty much anything

1089
00:51:00,538 --> 00:51:02,459
and your audience is gonna be along the ride with you.

1090
00:51:02,479 --> 00:51:03,599
At least that's my belief.

1091
00:51:07,625 --> 00:51:08,788
All right, that's all I got.

1092
00:51:08,988 --> 00:51:09,990
Thank you guys so much for coming.

1093
00:51:10,211 --> 00:51:10,632
Appreciate it.

